# PR review bot replies

Same standard as Australian Rates: **`WORKFLOW.md`** step 6.

**Summary:** for every substantive thread from automated reviewers, reply with the disposition (implemented + SHA / deferred + reason / declined + reason) **and resolve the thread on GitHub**. This repo enables `required_conversation_resolution`, so resolution — not the reply — is what unblocks merge; a replied-but-unresolved thread stays blocked. Resolution alone satisfies the `bot-feedback-gate` (no keyword reply needed); reply wording, where used, is matched forgivingly but negations like "not fixed" do not count. Green CI alone does not replace thread closure.

**Self-healing — never push empty "re-trigger" commits.** `bot-feedback-gate` re-runs on review/review-comment activity, and the gates run `cancel-in-progress: false`, so a `BLOCKED`-but-all-green PR with 0 unresolved threads just needs the next event or `gh run rerun <run-id>` on the PR head, not a synthetic commit. (`gh pr merge --auto` only enables auto-merge — it does not re-run a stale gate.) GitHub emits no webhook on *resolve*, so after a resolve-only round re-run via an inline review-thread reply (`pull_request_review_comment`, runs on the PR head), a push, or `gh run rerun <run-id>` of the existing PR-head run. A top-level PR comment (`issue_comment`) and a bare `gh workflow run … -f pr_number` both run against the default branch, so their check won't attach to the PR head.

**Gate:** `npm run pr:bot-feedback-check -- --pr <n>` must exit **0** before squash merge. Check overall readiness in one call with `npm run pr:gates:check -- --pr <n>` instead of hand-polling `gh`. CI jobs **`bot-presence-gate`** and **`bot-feedback-gate`** must be green when branch protection is enabled. Post-merge: `npm run pr:bot-feedback-audit` then in-thread replies + fix PR if needed.
